{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Persist ticket digest as a REVIEW_RESULT-style sidecar record on the ticket (shared cache)\n\n## Why\nThe digest is a billable LLM artifact we never want to recompute. Storing it in the SHARED store (auto-pushed) makes one client's enrichment a cache-hit for every other client. rebar already has the exact precedent: `REVIEW_RESULT` — a reducer-IGNORED, preserved-and-ignored, per-ticket LLM-derived sidecar event. We reuse that pattern rather than inventing a reducer-projected type, avoiding compaction/SNAPSHOT entanglement.\n\n## What\nA new `TICKET_DIGEST` sidecar event carrying the S1 digest plus a `content_hash` of the fields it was derived from. Freshness is computed on read: the digest is CURRENT iff its stored `content_hash` (and `model`/`schema` version tags) match the ticket's current values; otherwise it reads as stale. Latest-wins: a scan reduces to the most-recent `TICKET_DIGEST` per ticket (by HLC order), so re-enrichment supersedes rather than accumulates in the projection.\n\n## Scope (exact edit targets — every registry a new event type touches)\n- `src/rebar/_store/event_append.py`: add `\"TICKET_DIGEST\"` to the `EVENT_TYPES` write allow-list (line ~38) or `stage_and_commit` raises StoreError.\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_version.py`: add `\"TICKET_DIGEST\"` to `_NON_REPLAY_KNOWN_TYPES` (line 44), NOT `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES` — so it is preserved-and-ignored by the main reducer, is never squashed into SNAPSHOT by compaction, and never trips the fsck \"newer-than-binary\" warning (mirrors REVIEW_RESULT exactly).\n- A scan/read helper (mirror how REVIEW_RESULT sidecars are read) that returns the current digest per ticket for the retrieval stage; `content_hash` helper over a NAMED, versioned field set (`DIGEST_HASH_FIELDS` = title + description + comment bodies, normalized: strip trailing whitespace, join with \"\\n\"). Bump a `DIGEST_HASH_VERSION` when the field set changes so all cached digests invalidate deterministically.\n- `show` renders digest presence + freshness only (not the raw digest text); the raw digest is available to retrieval. No new field in `ticket_state.schema.json` (sidecar, not compiled state), matching REVIEW_RESULT.\n- Fail-closed freshness: if the current content-hash cannot be computed (partial read), the digest reads as NOT-current (never falsely fresh) — mirroring `compute_validity` returning None on read error.\n- Prune/retire: a digest for a deleted/archived ticket is dropped by the same prune path REVIEW_RESULT uses (name it); document that concurrent same-ticket digests from two clients are safe — both are TICKET_DIGEST appends, latest-by-HLC wins on read, idempotent.\n\n## Dependencies\nS1 (indecisive-callous-armyworm) — produces the `ticket_digest` payload this stores.\n\n## Testing\n- Unit `tests/unit/test_ticket_digest_store.py`: write→read roundtrip; freshness flips stale when title/description/comment changes; fail-closed on unreadable state; latest-wins on two appends; older binary preserves-and-ignores the event (fsck no WARN); archived ticket's digest pruned.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A digest is written via a `TICKET_DIGEST` event and read back per ticket; verified by `pytest tests/unit/test_ticket_digest_store.py::test_roundtrip`.\n- [ ] Freshness is computed on read: mutating any `DIGEST_HASH_FIELDS` field marks the digest stale; verified by `::test_freshness_flips`.\n- [ ] `TICKET_DIGEST` is in `EVENT_TYPES` and `_NON_REPLAY_KNOWN_TYPES` (not `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES`); an older binary preserves-and-ignores it with no fsck WARN.\n- [ ] Unreadable current state yields NOT-current (fail-closed), never falsely fresh.\n- [ ] Two concurrent same-ticket digest appends resolve latest-by-HLC on read (idempotent, no duplication); an archived/deleted ticket's digest is pruned.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783572140740997001,"uuid":"a4acae8b-5348-433c-b4ad-e982c617bcc3"}